==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fuss
<hw>Fuss</hw> <pr>(f⟦ucr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Fusome</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A tumult; a bustle; unnecessary
or annoying ado about trifles.</def> <rj><au>Byron.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Zealously, assiduously, and with a minimum of <qex>fuss</qex> or
noise</q> <rj><qau>Carlyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who is unduly anxious about trifles; a
fussbudget.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am a <qex>fuss</qex> and I don't deny it.</q> <rj><qau>W. D.
Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fuss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fuss
<hw>Fuss</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fussed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fussing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To be overbusy or unduly anxious
about trifles; to make a bustle or ado.</def> <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fussbudget</ent>⟦br⟧
